{
  "segments": [
    {
      "index": 0,
      "text": "You have fifty Pods running.",
      "start": 2.0,
      "end": 3.8987,
      "duration": 1.8987
    },
    {
      "index": 1,
      "text": "Some are in production. Some are in staging.",
      "start": 4.2787,
      "end": 7.2013,
      "duration": 2.9227
    },
    {
      "index": 2,
      "text": "Some are backends, some are frontends.",
      "start": 7.5813,
      "end": 10.184,
      "duration": 2.6027
    },
    {
      "index": 3,
      "text": "How does Kubernetes even know which is which?",
      "start": 10.564,
      "end": 13.572,
      "duration": 3.008
    },
    {
      "index": 4,
      "text": "The answer is Labels. Two words. A colon. Maximum power.",
      "start": 13.952,
      "end": 18.4747,
      "duration": 4.5227
    },
    {
      "index": 5,
      "text": "Labels let you attach arbitrary metadata to any object \u2014 and then query, route, and manage objects in bulk using that metadata.",
      "start": 18.8547,
      "end": 27.9213,
      "duration": 9.0667
    },
    {
      "index": 6,
      "text": "Selectors are what make the queries possible.",
      "start": 28.3013,
      "end": 31.5867,
      "duration": 3.2853
    },
    {
      "index": 7,
      "text": "This is episode thirteen. Labels and Selectors. Let's go.",
      "start": 31.9667,
      "end": 36.212,
      "duration": 4.2453
    }
  ],
